  "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
  "body": "**Envoy version**: v1.9.1\r\n\r\nWe're seeing an issue where Envoy sometimes leaks tens of gigabytes of memory. I still don't have a great understanding of why this is happening, but here's what we know so far.\r\n\r\nHere's the output of pprof on a heap profile: https://gist.github.com/julia-stripe/04cee10b2185d81f1b84ad493920a9b3 which I think is saying that the memory is being allocated on [this line](https://github.com/envoyproxy/envoy/blame/53781eb42fdfce56ec3b187dc551344ab4f4a86f/source/extensions/transport_sockets/tls/ssl_socket.cc#L86).\r\n\r\nSome other observations:\r\n\r\n[Here are some logs from the heap profiler](https://gist.github.com/julia-stripe/37311c46088ab00a45143f6d3395292e). It looks like the pattern is that it allocates ~8GB of memory, frees some memory, and then does the same thing again. There are a lot of periods where it's allocating about 1GB/s.\r\n\r\ntcmalloc doesn't seem to be doing a great job of releasing freed memory back to the OS though: this example of what's reported by the stats endpoint is pretty typical (16MB allocated, 17GB heap). \r\n\r\n```\r\n$ curl localhost:9901/stats | grep memory\r\nserver.memory_allocated: 16697176\r\nserver.memory_heap_size: 17301504000\r\n```\r\n\r\nA few more relevant statistics that make this confusing:\r\n\r\n* [output](https://gist.github.com/julia-stripe/176fcd4251af6237416d92b7e60a0ad6) of `curl localhost:9901/stats | grep bytes` (less than 100GB of data)\r\n* [output](https://gist.github.com/julia-stripe/925b377e9dfc9d9b899ece3156fe5ec1) of `curl localhost:9901/stats | grep cx_total` (only ~2000 connections)",
